    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>States and Health Care</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Assemblyman Richard N Gottfried letter urges Congress to enact legislation giving patients right to sue health plan for wrongful denial of care, especially now that Supreme Court has limited that right (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The Supreme Court decision limiting the right of a patient to sue a health plan that wrongly denies care makes it more urgent that Congress enact legislation giving patients that right.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The Supreme Court decision limiting the right of a patient to sue a health plan that wrongly denies care makes it more urgent that Congress enact legislation giving patients that right.</p>
        <p>But I disagree that this ''can be addressed only by Congress'' (editorial, June 14).</p>
        <p>The decision appears to support the right of the states to let patients hold a health plan accountable when it wrongly denies care that was medically necessary, as long as the care was within the coverage of the health plan.</p>
        <p>Congress could also do that. But meanwhile, New York and other states should move forward.</p>
        <p>RICHARD N. GOTTFRIED  Chmn., Assembly Health Committee  Albany, June 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
